<p>
<seg id="1">A man carries out an acid attack but the court declares him not dangerous.</seg>
<seg id="2">You never know what can happen to you.</seg>
<seg id="3">One moment, you're at home laughing with your family, and the next your whole life is shaken to the core.</seg>
<seg id="4">And the worst thing is that you can't do anything about it at all.</seg>
<seg id="5">This is the fate that met Andreas Christopheros from Great Britain, whose face was burned with acid by an unknown attacker who was eventually acquitted.</seg>
<seg id="6">Reuters reported on the story.</seg>
<seg id="7">In December 2014, someone at knocked on the Christopheros' door.</seg>
<seg id="8">Andreas got up to open it.</seg>
<seg id="9">He thought that the person at the door was probably the courier who was supposed to deliver the Christmas gifts for the family that day.</seg>
<seg id="10">Instead, a terrible surprise awaited him.</seg>
<seg id="11">A man he had never seen in his life poured acid on him without warning as soon as he opened up, saying, "That's for you, friend."</seg>
<seg id="12">The pain was indescribable.</seg>
<seg id="13">My clothes dissolved into nothing, and I just felt an unreal pain on my skin," said Andreas.</seg>
<seg id="14">His family quickly took him to the hospital, but his relatives learned terrible news there - the doctors said he had no chance to survive.</seg>
<seg id="15">Several weeks after the incident, doctors were constantly worried that their patient would succumb to the infection that threatened to penetrate his wounds.</seg>
<seg id="16">His injuries were very serious.</seg>
<seg id="17">Ninety percent of his face was affected, and the doctors attempted to piece it back together with skin from other parts of the patient's body.</seg>
<seg id="18">One major complication for Christopheros was the loss of his eyelids.</seg>
<seg id="19">Without doubt, it's the most painful thing I've ever experienced.</seg>
<seg id="20">"You can't escape from unexpected light, you can't close your eyes," he said, describing his suffering.</seg>
<seg id="21">At this point, Christopheros has undergone twelve operations and is still far away from the last.</seg>
<seg id="22">According to plastic surgeons, injuries affecting sufferers of acid attacks can require hundreds of surgical interventions and years of healing.</seg>
<seg id="23">Even after demanding, long-term treatment, the victims still have scar tissue for the rest of their lives.</seg>
<seg id="24">"Sometimes people do not recover, and they fight deformity and disfigurement throughout their lives," said Peter Dziewulski, a spokesperson for the British Association of Plastic and Aesthetic Surgeons.</seg>
<seg id="25">The attacker made a mistake.</seg>
<seg id="26">In terms of the attack, Christopheros is convinced that the unknown man must have confused him with someone else.</seg>
<seg id="27">The perpetrator believed that he was taking revenge on a man who had sexually abused someone close to him.</seg>
<seg id="28">The police investigated the case thoroughly and finally tracked down the assailant.</seg>
<seg id="29">The man was originally sentenced to at least eight years in prison.</seg>
<seg id="30">However, the verdict was later fundamentally altered, much to the astonishment of Christopher's family.</seg>
<seg id="31">"Three judges eventually concluded that the sentence should be abolished because the man was not considered to be a threat to the public," said Christopheros.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number attacks using corrosive substances has increased considerably over the past few years.</seg>
<seg id="33">The UK Ministry of the Interior has announced that it plans to tackle the issue by issuing new guidelines to prosecutors concerning the classification of corrosives.</seg>
<seg id="34">They should be classified as dangerous weapons.</seg>
<seg id="35">However, the victims of these attacks are unwilling to give up.</seg>
<seg id="36">They are demanding that the UK Government enforce stricter and longer prison sentences for people attacking their surroundings with acid or other corrosive substances.</seg>
<seg id="37">They are also calling for tighter controls on the sale of dangerous substances, which are often commonly available in many shops since they consist of various cleaning products.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
