<doc sysid="ref" docid="idnes.cz.293443" genre="news" origlang="cs">
<p>
<seg id="1">China is lacking tourists.</seg>
<seg id="2">Beijing is losing billions because of the national visa policies.</seg>
<seg id="3">For decades, China has been trying to exert its influence without the use of force.</seg>
<seg id="4">It spends 10 billion dollars a year to support language schools and establish universities abroad, pushing its entertainment industry towards foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.</seg>
<seg id="5">It isn't doing anything for Beijing, however.</seg>
<seg id="6">The local state media has been talking about a plan to make tourism a driving force for economic transformation and modernisation.</seg>
<seg id="7">However, the number of visitors grew by only 3.8 percent last year, and about 80 percent China's tourists came from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.</seg>
<seg id="8">Among other things, this is due to the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, the Chinese Foreign Minister does not welcome foreigners with open arms. At least this is how Christopher Balding, Professor of Economics at Beijing University, assessed the situation in the most populous country of the world in an article for Bloomberg.</seg>
<seg id="9">One particularly indicative example is the Chinese visa policy.</seg>
<seg id="10">Only 13 countries have visa-free entry to China, while the citizens of the others have to organise visas in advance.</seg>
<seg id="11">As such, the Chinese offices in the US have crowds comparable to the Chinese New Year celebrations.</seg>
<seg id="12">The visa costs 140 dollars, but if you do not want to wait in the queue for hours, you have to pay 100 dollars or more for additional services.</seg>
<seg id="13">These kinds of restrictions create significant economic barriers.</seg>
<seg id="14">A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for visas reduces the visitor numbers by 70 percent.</seg>
<seg id="15">In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while 1.8 million Americans went to Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's gross domestic product and is home to less than one percent of its population.</seg>
<seg id="16">China often worsens this problem when it uses tourist activities to pursue its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.</seg>
<seg id="17">When China restricted transportation to South Korea during a rift concerning the South Korean missile defence system, the South Koreans retaliated by avoiding China.</seg>
<seg id="18">In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent from the previous year, whereas in Japan the same figure grew by 85 percent.</seg>
<seg id="19">All this affects macroeconomic stability.</seg>
<seg id="20">According to a recently published report by the Fed (the American Federal Reserve), up to 190 billion dollars may have left China as a result of foreign trips by Chinese people, while China only gains around 35 billion dollars a year through sales of foreign currency to incoming tourists.</seg>
<seg id="21">According to the official figures for the development of the balance of payments, last year China had a deficit of 217 billion dollars in terms of tourism, equivalent to 44 percent of the entire Chinese surplus in commodities trading.</seg>
<seg id="22">This small number of tourists comes as a very painful blow to a country that has anxiously protected the flow of capital.</seg>
<seg id="23">However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of more a general restraint in relation to foreigners.</seg>
<seg id="24">In many parts of China, practically nobody has heard about immigrants.</seg>
<seg id="25">In 2013, there were fewer than a million foreigners living in China.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the United States, however, there are more of them living in certain cities.</seg>
<seg id="27">Even Japan, which is not known as the crossroads of immigration, has twice as many foreign inhabitants.</seg>
<seg id="28">Many scientific papers have shown that immigrants usually revive economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.</seg>
<seg id="29">It is almost impossible to find in China, however.</seg>
<seg id="30">Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the first step is to simplify the visa system.</seg>
<seg id="31">Other Asian countries, especially India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and reduce visa procedures.</seg>
<seg id="32">If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc sysid="ref" docid="blesk.cz.110859" genre="news" origlang="cs">
<p>
<seg id="1">The number of deadly poisonous reptiles at Pilsen Zoo has increased.</seg>
<seg id="2">At the Království jedu (Poison Kingdom) in Pilsen, visitors can now look forward to seeing the young of three rare, deadly poisonous reptiles.</seg>
