<p>
<seg id="1">Russian athletes have not had their ban on starting lifted by the IAAF.</seg>
<seg id="2">During its congress in London, the IAAF International Athletics Federation upheld the international ban preventing the Russian athletes from starting because of the state-sponsored doping programme.</seg>
<seg id="3">The result vote regarding the world championships, which begin on Friday, was unambiguous, as expected.</seg>
<seg id="4">The prolongation of the ban was approved by 166 delegates, with only 21 votes opposing it.</seg>
<seg id="5">The main reason for the rejection is that Russia has failed to meet all the requirements for the introduction of the anti-doping system, as noted by Rune Andersen, the head of the IAAF Special Investigation Group.</seg>
<seg id="6">His group recommended that the ban be upheld.</seg>
<seg id="7">Some older doping cases remain unresolved, as a number of suspected athletes have not yet been heard, and coaches with a compromised reputation are still working in the country.</seg>
<seg id="8">The Russian anti-doping agency RUSADA is not yet fully operational, and does not meet the standards of the World Anti-Doping Agency.</seg>
<seg id="9">However, RUSADA may undergo testing under the supervision of foreign experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency.</seg>
<seg id="10">"Although progress has been made, there is still a lot of work to be done," said IAAF Chairman Sebastian Coe.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Russian Athletic Federation was suspended in November 2015, meaning Russian athletes were not able to attend last year's Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro.</seg>
<seg id="12">Despite the ban on the upcoming international championships, 19 Russians who have previously proved they have been tested outside of the Russian anti-doping system for a long time will participate.</seg>
<seg id="13">However, they will not be able to start championships wearing the national colours, and in the event of a victory, the Russian anthem will not be played.</seg>
</p>
