<seg id="1">D11, or how not to build a motorway.</seg>
<seg id="2">Can the motorways in the Czech Republic ever be finished?</seg>
<seg id="3">Here's a puzzle for you.</seg>
<seg id="4">It is unfinished, even though construction started in 1978.</seg>
<seg id="5">Even though it hasn't materialised, it is constantly being repaired.</seg>
<seg id="6">It can't be built, even though it has a building permit.</seg>
<seg id="7">What is it?</seg>
<seg id="8">Yes, that's right, motorway D11 to Hradec Králové.</seg>
<seg id="9">Construction on another section of it has recently halted by the Děti Země (Children of the Earth) movement for at least several months.</seg>
<seg id="10">We Eastern Bohemians are getting our motorway in pieces, like cutting slices off a salami.</seg>
<seg id="11">One round is sliced and then we have to wait and see if and when we'll get another.</seg>
<seg id="12">We're not asking for miracles, though.</seg>
<seg id="13">We just want to shorten driving times and to divert trucks going to or from Poland away from villages and towns.</seg>
<seg id="14">The endless streams of trucks go straight through the towns like Jaroměř or Náchod, which cannot be reasonably avoided.</seg>
<seg id="15">The final stretch of our dream motorway was begun in 2008, that is, an unbelievable nine years ago.</seg>
<seg id="16">Since then, there hasn't been a modicum of progress.</seg>
<seg id="17">Therefore, when construction began on the remaining four kilometres of the incomplete section to Hradec Králové and an archaeological survey was carried out other sections by Jaroměř, with works due to begin at the end of this year, you could hear corks being popped loudly in Eastern Bohemia.</seg>
<seg id="18">At this point, nobody believed it however.</seg>
<seg id="19">Last week it was announced that construction will not take place this year.</seg>
<seg id="20">And maybe not next year either.</seg>
<seg id="21">Děti Země, an organisation from Brno fighting for sustainable transport, has put a halt on the works.</seg>
<seg id="22">Děti Země is repeating its tactics from D1.</seg>
<seg id="23">They opposed the decision to grant the building permit in its entirety.</seg>
<seg id="24">They are demanding a review of all the binding opinions already issued by all authorities involved.</seg>
<seg id="25">For example, these include the City of Hradec Králové, the Ministry of the Environment, but also the Ministry of Defence and the Railway Authority.</seg>
<seg id="26">Meanwhile, not far from D11 we come across the village with the expressive name of Pohřebačka.</seg>
<seg id="27">We drive down, we simply continue along the motorway and all of a sudden we find ourselves on the side road next to it so we can join the line of traffic.</seg>
<seg id="28">The worst part is that you can see similar stories across the country.</seg>
<seg id="29">There's the terrifying, constantly clogged road to Benešov, the D1 or D8 motorways.</seg>
<seg id="30">Everyone has their own Pohřebačka.</seg>
<seg id="31">What did Děti Země request?</seg>
<seg id="32">What is the at the heart of the problems with road construction in the Czech Republic?</seg>
<seg id="33">And why is motorway network practically impossible to finish within the current system?</seg>
<seg id="34">Read more in the new edition of Reflex.</seg>
