<seg id="6">There, at the beginning of the historical overview, it states that the camp lay two kilometres east of the village of Lety, that it served as a labour camp from 8 August 1940, as a displaced persons camp from 1 January 1942 and became a Roma camp on 2 August 1942.</seg>
<seg id="7">The text below this goes on to describe life in the camp, including inhumane conditions, until March 1943, when Lety's first prisoners were assigned to the Auschwitz transport.</seg>
<seg id="8">On 4 May 1943, 370 people were transported to the extermination camp.</seg>
<seg id="9">The overall total was 420.</seg>
<seg id="10">It is a very sad history of enormous suffering on the part of human beings caused to them by human beings and perverse ideology.</seg>
<seg id="11">There is no question about the need to remember these events constantly.</seg>
<seg id="12">There is also no question that the remembrance should take place at the memorial located in the place where these people suffered.</seg>
<seg id="13">The problem lies elsewhere.</seg>
<seg id="14">During socialism, the camp was slightly forgotten about, and in the 1970s a pig farm was built near and on the part of the former camp.</seg>
<seg id="15">The history of the camp was accidentally discovered in 1992 by American Paul Polansky, and a memorial was erected at Lety in 1995.</seg>
<seg id="16">In the mid-1990s, the government promised to buy and demolish the pig farm, but so far it has not happened.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 1998, the monument was declared a cultural monument and since 2009 its administration has been governed by the Lidice Memorial.</seg>
<seg id="18">In July 2013, the UN Human Rights Committee called on the Czech Republic to close the pig farm.</seg>
<seg id="19">These are facts about the camp's post-war fate in brief.</seg>
<seg id="20">At least, that was until autumn of this year, when the government approved the purchase of the pig farm and decided to call an expert judgment to determine the price.</seg>
<seg id="21">According to the Minister of Agriculture, the government is rumoured to buying the pig farm back after.</seg>
<seg id="22">According to Minister of Culture Herman, "there are some figures, but I would probably upset the plans if I went to the public with them."</seg>
<seg id="23">We'll see what the expert opinion leads to.</seg>
<seg id="24">According to some unofficial estimates, it may amount to hundreds of millions, while according to others the price may reach up to a billion.</seg>
<seg id="25">In any case, it will definitely not be a cheap matter.</seg>
<seg id="26">And just a few hundred metres from the former camp is a memorial in which the state invested almost 10 million crowns in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="27">Even if the whole transaction were funded by the UN Human Rights Committee, which obviously is not likely, in my opinion it would still be a waste of money.</seg>
<seg id="28">Doesn't the government have other priorities?</seg>
<seg id="29">The memorial, a solemn place of commemoration, stands there thanks to the will of history, almost in the immediate vicinity of the tragedy, and anyone who wants to can go there to pay tribute to the memory of those who suffered and were killed.</seg>
<seg id="30">I don't see any reason to change it!</seg>
<seg id="31">Let's just leave it as it is, and maintain the site of reverence with the utmost care.</seg>
<seg id="32">The property, and now also the taxpayers' money, should be entrusted to a responsible person, in this case the government of the Czech Republic, to oversee it with the care of a dutiful manager.</seg>
<seg id="33">They should at least treat it as if it were their own company.</seg>
<seg id="34">Of course, the Minister of Finance and the Deputy Prime Minister do not represent the whole government.</seg>
<seg id="35">However, given the aforementioned facts, I feel that the leader of the ANO movement is only using it as an empty pre-election proclamation.</seg>
<seg id="36">This May I went directly to the place to see it.</seg>
<seg id="37">It has a good driveway, orderly parking and replicas of the wooden camp huts.</seg>
<seg id="38">There is an exhibition in one, and an integrated toilet with running water in another.</seg>
<seg id="39">There is a small, outdoor amphitheater with a seating area and a view of the memorial site, made from stones placed on a slight slope.</seg>
<seg id="40">There are a lot of flowers and wreaths.</seg>
<seg id="41">All the attributes correspond to the meaning of this place, and are suitable and appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="42">Archaeological research is currently taking place on the site of the original camp.</seg>
<seg id="43">It would be reasonable to consider whether it would be possible to preserve some of the uncovered foundations, for example, and at least make them accessible in an appropriate visual manner.</seg>
<seg id="44">Minister of Culture Daniel Herman could be focussing his efforts in this direction.</seg>
<seg id="45">If he succeeds in pushing the government to buy a pig farm with state money, it will be just another unfortunate step in his already problematic time in the role of Minister of Culture.</seg>
</p>
