<p>
<seg id="1">Police dogs trained in helicopter flights in Most</seg>
<seg id="2">Dogs specialised in hunting explosives and search dogs were trained in a helicopter flight over Most lake today.</seg>
<seg id="3">Police dogs must not be cowardly or scared of flying, said Petr Tomášek, head of police cynologists for the Ústí nad Labem region.</seg>
<seg id="4">Police dog training takes around two years.</seg>
<seg id="5">At Most, previously educated dogs were trained like adults, and those who are not yet trained just passed by.</seg>
<seg id="6">In addition to the standard training, which involves being exposed to specimens of explosives around the lake and looking for a lost figurine, all 12 animals had to board the helicopter and fly over the lake.</seg>
<seg id="7">The main purpose of the exercise is to test the dogs in the helicopter.</seg>
<seg id="8">The dogs had to get to work to as soon as the helicopter landed so that they didn't have problems with it moving.</seg>
<seg id="9">"The helicopter lands, then the dog goes and starts searching immediately," said Tomášek.</seg>
<seg id="10">Dogs that that are upset or unable to start working as the helicopter flies are excluded from training.</seg>
<seg id="11">"They are usually kept in the garden by the handlers, for example," Tomas added.</seg>
<seg id="12">The police have 76 dogs with different specialties in the Ústí region.</seg>
<seg id="13">German shepherds are the dominant breed, but there are also a growing number of Belgian shepherds.</seg>
<seg id="14">The handlers take care of them from the time they are puppies.</seg>
<seg id="15">"They raise them alone, preparing the dogs for the service they will perform for us," Tomášek added.</seg>
<seg id="16">The animals undergo repeated veterinary tests to reveal any possible health issues or disabilities.</seg>
<seg id="17">If the dog is healthy and not timid, they take the first test at 20 months.</seg>
<seg id="18">"It takes about two and a half to three years to get a precise aim," Tomášek added.</seg>
<seg id="19">Their time in the police service depends on the dog's health.</seg>
<seg id="20">Most of them remain for around 8 to 10 years.</seg>
<seg id="21">They generally live with their handlers.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
