<p>
<seg id="1">Unique brewery brews beer once again.</seg>
<seg id="2">The newly revived brewery is back serving up good beer.</seg>
<seg id="3">The passion and honesty of the new owners brought the brewery in Lobeč u Mšena back to life a few years ago.</seg>
<seg id="4">The brewery was first commemorated in 1586 and has Renaissance foundations, and in the nineteenth century it was converted into a train depot.</seg>
<seg id="5">This was followed by years of prosperity, when the brewery was especially famous for its dark beers.</seg>
<seg id="6">Unfortunately, production was stopped during World War II and the brewery was nationalised in 1984.</seg>
<seg id="7">After that, the buildings served as state property.</seg>
<seg id="8">The demolition work was finished by the owners of the brewery after 1989.</seg>
<seg id="9">The abandoned site was devastated and stripped for building materials.</seg>
<seg id="10">However, in 2007 new hopes emerged in the form of new owners, architects Jana and Pavel Prouza.</seg>
<seg id="11">They began to repair the buildings with utmost respect for the spirit of the property, down to the smallest detail.</seg>
<seg id="12">They devoted themselves to carefully studying archive documents in an attempt to retain the original materials and building elements.</seg>
<seg id="13">The brewery has the same look as it did in the nineteenth century, when its golden era began.</seg>
<seg id="14">Their work has been rewarded by a declaration from Ministry of Culture proclaiming the brewery to be a cultural monument, and the building has also become part of the European Industrial Heritage Trail.</seg>
<seg id="15">In 2015, they festively revived the tradition of beer brewing.</seg>
<seg id="16">If you want to sample a great beer from Lobeč in the scenic countryside around Kokořín, you can visit the pub in the brewery grounds.</seg>
<seg id="17">When brewing the beer, they use water from the protected landscape area of Kokořín, malt from the fields in Lobeč and hops Žatec.</seg>
<seg id="18">In the beer you, you can taste traditional light lager as well as dark beers and specialties.</seg>
<seg id="19">Don't miss out on the tour of the brewery, which is held on Saturdays and Sundays at midday and 13:30.</seg>
<seg id="20">The largest defensive fortress in Czechoslovakia?</seg>
<seg id="21">One of the largest fortresses of its kind in the world?</seg>
<seg id="22">This unique building was supposed to be the Stachelberg fortress between Trutnov and Žacléř, at the top of the ridge of terrain above the village of Babí.</seg>
<seg id="23">Originally, it should have been formed of up to 12 bunkers connected by a cavernous underground area.</seg>
<seg id="24">This was where the headquarters, barracks, ammunition, supplies, power generator, engine room and hospital would have been.</seg>
<seg id="25">However, the Munich Agreement put an end to it.</seg>
<seg id="26">In less than a year, it was only possible to build a single massive reinforced concrete bunker and the underground spaces cut off.</seg>
<seg id="27">Thanks to enthusiasts from the Stachelberg society, who started to reconstruct the unique building in the early 1990, you can also see it for yourselves.</seg>
<seg id="28">Seventy five percent of the underground area is already accessible!</seg>
<seg id="29">In addition to the T-S 73 infantry cabin with an exhibition and the underground area, there is also an armed light fortification building, two deployed infantry cabins, trenches and a nature trail by "Opevněné Trutnovsko".</seg>
<seg id="30">Refreshments, a homey alcove and breathtaking views of the region are guaranteed!</seg>
<seg id="31">This unique and amazing Czech building has been on a list alongside such sights as the Great Wall of China, Trajan's harbour near Rome, or the Assyrian palaces in Nineveh and Nimrud.</seg>
<seg id="32">The Chotěšov Monastery dates back to the beginning of the thirteenth century, and today it mainly consists of a stately four-wing convent building overlooking an exquisite garden.</seg>
<seg id="33">Unfortunately, the list it belongs to is that of unique buildings that are in danger of collapse.</seg>
<seg id="34">However, its devotees do not want to give up, and a lot of events are being held to support the monastery.</seg>
<seg id="35">One of them is the annual dinner for the Chotěšov Monastery, which will take place on Saturday 5 August. Vladimír Mišík amd Ivan Hlas will perform, you can see fencing duels and look at the amazing huge buildings, which are usually inaccessible.</seg>
<seg id="36">Above all, you can enjoy the atmosphere of this incredible place.</seg>
<seg id="37">Do you want to look a Neanderthal in the face?</seg>
<seg id="38">The exhibition Vítejte u neandertálců (Welcome to the Land of the Neanderthals) in the Anthropos Pavilion of the Moravian Museum in Brno is beckoning visitors to go an unusual excursion into the deepest prehistoric times right back to the Stone Age and the world of our ancestors.</seg>
<seg id="39">You will find out how the Neanderthals were able to cope perfectly with all sorts of extreme climate conditions, especially with the alternation of ice and inter-glacial ages.</seg>
<seg id="40">Despite their simple material culture, they were extremely successful as the predators of their time.</seg>
<seg id="41">You will also learn about their appearance, their anatomy, their technological and hunting skills, as well as their aesthetic sense.</seg>
<seg id="42">You wouldn't call them Neanderthals?</seg>
<seg id="43">Let yourself be convinced in Brno.</seg>
<seg id="44">The fourteenth KELT & WORLD MUSIC festival is held on Saturday the 5th in Veveří castle.</seg>
<seg id="45">In addition to excellent music, you'll see a Celtic village being built and experience the Celtic lifestyle, including crafts, games for children and adults, divination, magic and ritual body painting.</seg>
<seg id="46">Don't miss La Quadrilla with Irish and Scottish dances, drum jamming, bagpipe playing and a terrific fire surprise presented by Carpe Nocte.</seg>
<seg id="47">How does the Moravian-Silesian region taste?</seg>
<seg id="48">The seventh anniversary of the famous gastro-festival "Jak šmakuje Moravskoslezsko" (How does the Moravian-Silesian Region taste) takes place on Saturday 5 August 2017, in the mountain spa area of Karlova Studánka.</seg>
<seg id="49">The cooking will be provided by chef Miroslav Kalina, and you can sample culinary specialties and regional food and enjoy a musical and dance performance. There is also rich programme for children including creative workshops, theatre, a bouncy castle, a Smurf prize pathway and, of course, a number of competitions.</seg>
</p>
